  • what is ARD?
  • what is the difference between ARD, data cubes, and image collections?
  • must ARD, or a data cube, have a regular time discretisation?
  • What is a coverage, as defined e.g. by OGC in the web coverage service?
  • is an image collection always a coverage?
  • what does the stack method do in the BDC, for temporal aggregation?
  • why, in the Maus et al. paper, do the authors propose time-weighted dynamic time warping, as opposed to regular dynamic time warping?

R’s matrix() and image()

m = matrix(1:12, 3, 4)
m
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    4    7   10
## [2,]    2    5    8   11
## [3,]    3    6    9   12
image(m)

fortunes::fortune("conventions")
## 
## Mathematical conventions are just that, conventions. They differ by field of
## mathematics. Don't ask us why matrix rows are numbered down but graphs are
## numbered up the y axis, nor why x comes before y but row before column. But the
## matrix layout has always seemed illogical to me.
##    -- Brian D. Ripley (answering a question why the layouts of print(x) and
##       image(x) are different)
##       R-help (August 2004)
image2 = function(x, ...) {
    x = t(x) # transpose
    x = x[,ncol(x):1] # flip
    image(x, ...)
}
image2(m)

n = 25; m = 20
a = array(runif(n * m), c(n, m))
dim(a)
## [1] 25 20
image2(a, asp = 1)

fw = 5 # filter width
a1 = apply(a, 1, filter, filter = rep(1, fw)/fw)
image2(a1, asp = 1)

We applied the filter to the rows of the matrix, but see the correlation appear in the columns of the resulting matrix. This is because apply puts the dimension over which we iterated (rows) last, so rows have become colums:

dim(a1)
## [1] 20 25

We can further process this two get filtering (moving averaging) on the second dimension, which is again rows of a1:

a2 = apply(a1, 1, filter, filter = rep(1, fw)/fw)
image2(a2, asp = 1)

dim(a2)
## [1] 25 20

We see that the border two rows and columns are all NA:

a2[1:5,1:5]
##      [,1] [,2]      [,3]      [,4]      [,5]
## [1,]   NA   NA        NA        NA        NA
## [2,]   NA   NA        NA        NA        NA
## [3,]   NA   NA 0.5030802 0.4636314 0.4958934
## [4,]   NA   NA 0.5009663 0.4988115 0.4923284
## [5,]   NA   NA 0.4989709 0.5229027 0.4837181

We can also apply functions that erase the dimension, e.g. mean:

apply(a2, 1, mean, na.rm = TRUE) # row means
##  [1]       NaN       NaN 0.5150247 0.5155540 0.5112119 0.5330386 0.5293556
##  [8] 0.5220083 0.5066967 0.4888147 0.4756176 0.4883143 0.4692836 0.4828359
## [15] 0.4951025 0.4913600 0.4960115 0.4983032 0.4850099 0.4749165 0.4932965
## [22] 0.4586017 0.4471181       NaN       NaN
apply(a2, 2, mean, na.rm = TRUE) # column means
##  [1]       NaN       NaN 0.4724487 0.4745742 0.4857714 0.5030125 0.4971363
##  [8] 0.4901654 0.4761683 0.4590799 0.4721561 0.5074058 0.5023243 0.5085452
## [15] 0.5167100 0.5190740 0.4987515 0.5233244       NaN       NaN
mean(a2, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.4941655

real data

tif = system.file("tif/L7_ETMs.tif", package = "stars") # a Landsat-7 image part inside the package
r = read_stars(tif)
r
## stars object with 3 dimensions and 1 attribute
## attribute(s):
##   L7_ETMs.tif    
##  Min.   :  1.00  
##  1st Qu.: 54.00  
##  Median : 69.00  
##  Mean   : 68.91  
##  3rd Qu.: 86.00  
##  Max.   :255.00  
## dimension(s):
##      from  to  offset delta                       refsys point values x/y
## x       1 349  288776  28.5 UTM Zone 25, Southern Hem... FALSE   NULL [x]
## y       1 352 9120761 -28.5 UTM Zone 25, Southern Hem... FALSE   NULL [y]
## band    1   6      NA    NA                           NA    NA   NULL
plot(r)

Note that: * offset, delta and refsys allow moving from array index to world coordinates, back and forth * the third dimension here refers to spectral bands, this can also be time, or third time + fourth band etc. * point registers (can register) whether cell values refer to points or areas (support) * values may give values (e.g. band names, or continuous values if discretisation of the dimensions is not regular) * [x] and [y] indicate which variables map the horizontal (hopefully: x and y) dimensions * a “discrete axis” can refer to a set of (unordered) geometries, leading to vector data cubes

sf::read_sf(system.file("gpkg/nc.gpkg", package = "sf"), "nc.gpkg") %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(prec)) -> nc # transform from NAD27 to WGS84
nc_outline = st_union(st_geometry(nc))
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_union assumes that they are planar
plot_hook = function() plot(nc_outline, border = 'red', add = TRUE)
prec %>%
  slice(index = 1:12, along = "time") %>%
  plot(downsample = c(5, 5, 1), hook = plot_hook)
